Some crosstalk simulations

Unless otherwise indicated, the following simulations were performed with the "large" feed that has a flat ~50% efficiency across the band.
This feed sticks out exactly 218 mm (this is the position at which it reaches that good efficiency).

Also, note that until indicated, these simulations were run without a balun. I will add a separate set of simulations for crosstalk with balun further down.

Adding a "sleeve" (or "fence")

I first simulated that setup in a simple 6 m dish with rim-to-rim distances of 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm.
I then simulated the exact same thing, but adding a cylindrical "sleeve" that starts at the edge of the dish and goes up 218 mm (the distance by which the feed sticks out).

Here is a visual representation of the setup of the polarizations and corresponding port numbers:

Also, the simulations are performed without a balun. Adding the baluns makes the S1,2 (=S2,1=S3,4=S4,3) go up to -32 dB at high frequencies, I will present that further down.

Note that for clarity, I only present S3,1 (=S1,3) because these are the only S-parameters that are not negligibly small in these simulations (apart from S1,1, S2,2, S3,3, and S4,4, of course). Here are all the (non-redundant) S-parameters, to justify my choice of presenting only S3,1:

As one can see, S2,1 (=S1,2=S3,4=S4,3) is infinitesimal in those simulations without balun (this will NOT be the case when I add a balun). Also, those crosstalks within the same dish shouldn't be significantly affected by adding a fence or changing the dish distances.
S4,1 (=S1,4=S3,2=S2,3) is also negligible, since they represent pairs of orthogonal polarizations in different dishes.
S4,2 (=S2,4) is around -60 dB, which is not negligible, but significantly lower than S3,1 (=S1,3), and it intuitively seems unlikely that, unless the polarizations are rotated, adding a fence or changing the dish distance in a way that decreases S3,1 would increase S4,2.
Hence, I only present S3,1 for the moment:

No sleeve, feed sticking out:
With sleeve that goes as high as the feed is sticking out:

Comment: we save ~5-10 dB in the most problematic part of the band (300-800 MHz) by adding the sleeves.

Making the dishes larger and deeper

I then simulate larger dishes by "continuing the parabola", i.e. I keep the focus at the same location but increase the diameter: this effectively increases the dish "height" or "depth" with respect to focus, which is what I want.
I increased the dish height by 10, 20, 40, and 80 cm.
Here are the corresponding diameters:

Added depth (mm) Total depth (mm) Corresponding diameter (mm)
0 1500 6000
100 1600 6197
200 1700 6387
400 1900 6753
800 2300 7430

Note that the feed is always sticking out 218 mm above the focus (which is at 1500 mm from the bottom of the dish, not at the height of the rim anymore), so, for instance, in the "200 mm added depth" case, the feed is just sticking out 18 mm.

I run the simulations with a constant rim-to-rim distance of 400 mm, and compare the results with the two cases presented above (simple 6 m dish, 6 m dish with fence) at the same distances.

I included a dataset called "Simple 6 m dish, V1.5 feed", which is a different feed, simulated below a simple 6 m dish. This setup has a broader main beam and lower boresight gain especially at high frequencies, but I include it for comparison purposes since we are also considering it.

Crosstalks within the same dish with balun

As mentioned before, all simulations presented above were performed without balun, for the simple reason that adding the balun adds mesh cells and makes the simulations longer.

Also, the only crosstalk presented were S1,3, because they are the only ones that go significantly higher than ~-60 dB without balun. With baluns, S2,1 (=S1,2=S3,4=S4,3) are significant.

I added a balun and ran the feed alone, to see the crosstalk between the two polarizations on the same feed. I will later run the same thing in dishes. The baluns setup looks like this:

Note that when one balun is installed, there are 4 alternate ways to place the other one (imagine rotating it 180 degrees around boresight, and then mirroring either position). The one presented here is the one with the lowest crosstalks (alternatives go all the way up to -20 dB). Here are the results:
